description.plain:
Thea Taylor (b. November 23, 2002), better known by her stage name carolesdaughter, is an up-and-coming singer, songwriter, and multi-instrumentalist from southern California. She started making music in February of 2020 with her first song “wish i wuz dead.”

Bouncing between five different high schools, she started doing drugs, falling down a rabbit hole and taking multiple trips to rehab. On the last trip, she made a promise to pursue music upon returning home. She didn’t start to gain much traction however until her breakout song “Violent” went viral on TikTok. It originally released on April 19, 2020, but wouldn’t be released onto all platforms until November 23, 2020 through the help of Arista Records and Sony Music Entertainment.

songs.title: Violent

description.plain:
“Violent” is the breakout single by carolesdaughter. Originally being released on April 19, 2020, the song didn’t gain much traction until October of 2020, after it went viral on TikTok.

carolesdaughter made a video talking about the sudden viralness of the song. In the video, she said:

I didnt realize this song was gonna blow up i just found a youtube beat i liked and recorded on my phone i cant put it on spotify bc copyright but itll stay on soundcloud dont worry thank u 2 everyone for the kind messages 💗

As said in her video, she wasn’t able to release the song officially onto all platforms due to complications with the beat, which was produced by HVLX. Then, through the help of Arista Records and Sony Music Entertainment, “Violent” was finally released officially onto all platforms on November 23, 2020, her 18th birthday.

songs.title: BRAT

description.plain:
This song could be interpreted as a song about being addicted to drugs, which is a recurring theme in Carolesdaughter’s songs.

The second verse could be them feeling misunderstood for their addictions, but they are actually a huge softie.

songs.title: ​My Mother Wants Me Dead

description.plain:
“my mother wants me dead”, like many of her other songs, are about her drug use. Here, it also centers around paranoia.
It’s ironic because she loves her mother very much and vice versa, to the point her stage name is her mother’s name.
In a live show Thea stated that when she showed her mom this song, she said something along the lines of “it’s very good! …..but the name-”.

Image of her live show.
